{"key":"post-8524788","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>8524788</id>\n<content>&lt;/font&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;small&quot;&gt;Quote:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;when i had 2 to 2-1/2 inches of substrate all was well, but on this one with 5&quot; the center is obviously the thickest area of substrate, im wondering if this has anything to do with it&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;post&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I've seen several threads here lately where noobs were giving advice to use deep substrates of 5&quot; and more.&amp;nbsp; Very few trays that deep are going to fruit properly unless you're growing agaricus on composted manure.&amp;nbsp; You can use a thick substrate like that with straw successfully, but not pf cakes.&amp;nbsp; Keep them to 2&quot; to 2 1/2&quot;.&amp;nbsp; Actually, for best total yield, fruit them as cakes and get several flushes.&amp;nbsp; Cased pf cakes rarely deliver a decent second flush, let alone six to seven flushes you'll get from fruiting them as cakes properly.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Don't worry too much about uneven pinsets.&amp;nbsp; With few exceptions, total yield will be similar because fewer mushrooms translates into larger mushrooms.&amp;nbsp; It's still cool to see wall to wall flushes, and it's something to shoot for, but don't sweat it.&amp;nbsp; Patching and careful attention to misting and maintenance is how you get those picture perfect flushes.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>8524853</next>\n<prev>8524767</prev>\n<first>7093376</first>\n<last>8524945</last>\n<when>1213496395</when>\n<utime>06/15/08 05:19 AM</utime>\n</post>"}